 "cells": [

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Basic Data Visualization\n",
    "\n",
    "[![Open In Colab](https://colab.research.google.com/assets/colab-badge.svg)](https://colab.research.google.com/github/jpn--/python-for-transportation-modeling/blob/master/course-content/visualization/two-dim-plots.ipynb)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Python offers a variety of data visualization packages, but\n",
    "the most fundamental, and most ubiquitous, is \n",
    "[matplotlib](https://matplotlib.org/index.html).\n",
    "Typically, this package most often used with the\n",
    "[pyplot](https://matplotlib.org/users/pyplot_tutorial.html)\n",
    "tools, which provides a plotting command interface similar to what\n",
    "you have with a tool like MATLAB."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:04.616112Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:03.683407Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from matplotlib import pyplot as plt\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import seaborn as sns"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For example, if you have some data like this:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:04.621657Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:04.618130Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "total_florida_vmt = pd.Series({\n",
    "    2003: 508_607_851,\n",
    "    2004: 537_494_319,\n",
    "    2005: 550_614_540,\n",
    "    2006: 558_308_386,\n",
    "    2007: 562_798_032,\n",
    "    2008: 542_334_376,\n",
    "    2009: 538_088_986,\n",
    "    2010: 536_315_479,\n",
    "    2011: 525_630_013,\n",
    "    2012: 522_879_155,\n",
    "    2013: 527_950_180,\n",
    "    2014: 550_795_629,\n",
    "    2015: 566_360_175,\n",
    "    2016: 588_062_806,\n",
    "    2017: 599_522_329,\n",
    "})"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You can draw a plot and label an axis as simply as this:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:04.716443Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:04.623875Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.plot(total_florida_vmt)\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"Total Statewide VMT\");"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You can also plot more than one thing on the same figure.\n",
    "For example, we can plot both VMT and a 5 year rolling\n",
    "average of VMT on the same figure, including a legend:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:04.810861Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:04.719297Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.plot(total_florida_vmt, label='Current Year VMT')\n",
    "plt.plot(total_florida_vmt.rolling(5).mean(), 'r--', label='5 Year Rolling Average')\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"Total Statewide VMT\")\n",
    "plt.legend();"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Multi-Dimensional Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In this section, we will look at some basic data visualization\n",
    "techniques for multi-dimensional data.  We'll begin by loading\n",
    "and preprocessing some data to analyze."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:05.027248Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:04.813272Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def data_url(filename):\n",
    "    url = \"https://github.com/jpn--/python-for-transportation-modeling/raw/master/example-package/transportation_tutorials/data/\"\n",
    "    return url + filename\n",
    "    \n",
    "def get_data(filename):\n",
    "    if not os.path.isfile(filename):\n",
    "        import urllib.request\n",
    "        urllib.request.urlretrieve(data_url(filename), filename)\n",
    "    return filename\n",
    "\n",
    "hh = pd.read_csv(get_data('SERPM8-BASE2015-HOUSEHOLDS.csv.gz'), index_col=0)\n",
    "persons = pd.read_csv(get_data('SERPM8-BASE2015-PERSONS.csv.gz'), index_col=0)\n",
    "trips = pd.read_csv(get_data('SERPM8-BASE2015-TRIPS.csv.gz'), index_col=0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:05.058049Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:05.028839Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Add household income to persons\n",
    "persons = persons.merge(hh.income, left_on='hh_id', right_on=hh.hh_id)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Count of persons per HH\n",
    "hh = hh.merge(\n",
    "    persons.groupby('hh_id').size().rename('hhsize'), \n",
    "    left_on=['hh_id'], \n",
    "    right_index=True,\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Count of trips per HH\n",
    "hh = hh.merge(\n",
    "    trips.groupby(['hh_id']).size().rename('n_trips'), \n",
    "    left_on=['hh_id'], \n",
    "    right_index=True,\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's look at what data we have now in the Households table."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:05.069913Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:05.059858Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "<class 'pandas.core.frame.DataFrame'>\n",
      "Int64Index: 17260 entries, 426629 to 568932\n",
      "Data columns (total 11 columns):\n",
      " #   Column        Non-Null Count  Dtype \n",
      "---  ------        --------------  ----- \n",
      " 0   hh_id         17260 non-null  int64 \n",
      " 1   home_mgra     17260 non-null  int64 \n",
      " 2   income        17260 non-null  int64 \n",
      " 3   autos         17260 non-null  int64 \n",
      " 4   transponder   17260 non-null  int64 \n",
      " 5   cdap_pattern  17260 non-null  object\n",
      " 6   jtf_choice    17260 non-null  int64 \n",
      " 7   autotech      17260 non-null  int64 \n",
      " 8   tncmemb       17260 non-null  int64 \n",
      " 9   hhsize        17260 non-null  int64 \n",
      " 10  n_trips       17260 non-null  int64 \n",
      "dtypes: int64(10), object(1)\n",
      "memory usage: 1.6+ MB\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "hh.info()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Scatter Plots"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Suppose we want to understand the relationship between\n",
    "household income and the number of trips taken.  We can\n",
    "create a scatterplot of the data using the `plot` method\n",
    "on the households `pandas.DataFrame`.  This function\n",
    "takes a `kind` argument that indicates what kind of plot\n",
    "to generate, plus `x` and `y` arguments that indicate the\n",
    "names of the columns in the DataFrame to plot."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:05.185757Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:05.071399Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "hh.plot(kind='scatter', x='income', y='n_trips');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There's a lot of data plotted here -- so much so that the more\n",
    "dense parts of the figure just look like a homogenous blob of\n",
    "blue. One way to change this figure to give it a little more\n",
    "context is to set the opacity (\"alpha\") for each point to a \n",
    "relatively small value. This results in the individual points \n",
    "being de-emphasized, and only areas where there is truely a \n",
    "preponderance of points become solid blue.  The `alpha` can\n",
    "be set as a keywork argument to the `plot` method:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:05.298909Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:05.188560Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "hh.plot(kind='scatter', x='income', y='n_trips', alpha=0.01);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This figure provides a bit more insight into the real distribution\n",
    "of the data: nearly all of it is in the area below \\$200K in household\n",
    "annual income.  If we want to focus our plot on that region, we can\n",
    "adjust the axis limits on the x axis, so that it only includes the \n",
    "zero to 200K range.  \n",
    "\n",
    "The `plot` method returns a matplotlib \n",
    "[Axes](https://matplotlib.org/api/axes_api.html#the-axes-class) \n",
    "object, which can be modified to give the desired result before \n",
    "the final figure is rendered.  In this case, we can use the \n",
    "`set_xlim` method to set the limits on the x axis:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:05.418585Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:05.302438Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ax = hh.plot(kind='scatter', x='income', y='n_trips', alpha=0.03)\n",
    "ax.set_xlim(0,200_000);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Plotting trip making against income is interesting, but what if we wanted\n",
    "to see the relationship between household size and automobile ownership?\n",
    "We could try the same approach:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:05.518561Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:05.420371Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "hh.plot(kind='scatter', x='hhsize', y='autos', alpha=0.01);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Unfortunately, there's not a lot of unique values for these two variables, \n",
    "and the thousands of points in the scatter plot are all overlaid on a very\n",
    "limited number of points in the figure.  While the opacity approach does \n",
    "permit a bit of differentiation between the unusual points and the others,\n",
    "it is hard to discern much information in the middle region of the figure.\n",
    "In fact, it may surprise someone viewing this figure that more than half of\n",
    "all the observation in the dataset occur on just two points.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Heatmaps\n",
    "\n",
    "Rather than a scatter plot, it may be more appropriate to visualize this\n",
    "data in a heatmap.  This kind of visualization will take the same information\n",
    "as displayed above, but rather than displaying the intensity of each point by\n",
    "layering partially transparent points, we can directly compute the mass of \n",
    "each point using a pivot table, and then display the data in a color coded\n",
    "table that is reasonably normalized to help highlight the information you want \n",
    "to convey.  To do this, we'll feed the data from a pivot table to the \n",
    "[heatmap](https://seaborn.pydata.org/generated/seaborn.heatmap.html) \n",
    "function from the `seaborn` package."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:05.753941Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:05.519878Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "sns.heatmap(\n",
    "    hh.pivot_table(\n",
    "        index='hhsize',\n",
    "        columns='autos',\n",
    "        aggfunc='size'\n",
    "    ).fillna(0),\n",
    "    annot=True,\n",
    "    fmt=\",.0f\"\n",
    ");"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The figure above much more clearly articulates the preponderance\n",
    "of observations in just 2 categories: one person-one car, and \n",
    "2 people-2 cars.  In fact, the over abundance of these two values\n",
    "is washing out much of the other detail in this visualization.\n",
    "As indicated in the documentation for the \n",
    "[heatmap](https://seaborn.pydata.org/generated/seaborn.heatmap.html) \n",
    "function, we can manually override the default upper bound of \n",
    "the colorscale by setting a `vmax` argument. This will set \n",
    "all of the values above the new maximum to the color at the\n",
    "maximum point. Since we are also using the `annot` argument \n",
    "to add annotations of the actual underlying values, it is still\n",
    "clear that the two peak values are well above the top of the\n",
    "colorscale, while a few other cells are shown with some more\n",
    "useful variation."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:06.065251Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:05.757061Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "sns.heatmap(\n",
    "    hh.pivot_table(\n",
    "        index='hhsize',\n",
    "        columns='autos',\n",
    "        aggfunc='size'\n",
    "    ).fillna(0),\n",
    "    annot=True,\n",
    "    fmt=\",.0f\",\n",
    "    vmax=1500,\n",
    ");"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The seaborn module provides a number of useful customization \n",
    "options as well, which are generally well documented online.\n",
    "For example, we can change the color scheme, adopting any \n",
    "[named colormap](https://matplotlib.org/tutorials/colors/colormaps.html) \n",
    "available in the matplotlib package."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:06.315509Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:06.067567Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "sns.heatmap(\n",
    "    hh.pivot_table(\n",
    "        index='hhsize',\n",
    "        columns='autos',\n",
    "        aggfunc='size'\n",
    "    ).fillna(0),\n",
    "    annot=True,\n",
    "    fmt=\",.0f\",\n",
    "    vmax=1500,\n",
    "    cmap=\"YlGnBu\",\n",
    ");"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Box Plots\n",
    "\n",
    "If one dimension to be visualized is discrete and the other \n",
    "is continuous, it may be useful to generate box plots to help\n",
    "compare distribution.  In these figures, the \"box\" at the middle\n",
    "of the plot covers the interquartile range (between the 25th and\n",
    "75th percentiles, the whiskers show some of the rest of the range\n",
    "(by default, up to 1.5 times the interquartile range), and dots\n",
    "show the remaining outliers."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:06.319772Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:06.317012Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Create a hhsize variable capped at 5\n",
    "hh['hhsize5'] = np.fmin(hh['hhsize'], 5)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:06.428257Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:06.321233Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "data = list(hh.groupby('hhsize5').income)\n",
    "plt.boxplot(\n",
    "    [i[1] for i in data],\n",
    "    vert=False,\n",
    "    labels=[i[0] for i in data],\n",
    ")\n",
    "plt.title('Household Income by Household Size')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Household Income')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Household Size');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The figure shown includes quite a lot of outliers across\n",
    "a very large range of incomes, but much of the detail in\n",
    "the highest echelons of income is not really important \n",
    "for transportation planning analysis.  We can adjust the\n",
    "figure's limits on the horizontal axis to focus in on the\n",
    "more relevant portion of the data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:06.532963Z",
     "start_time": "2022-05-31T19:20:06.429806Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.boxplot(\n",
    "    [i[1] for i in data],\n",
    "    vert=False,\n",
    "    labels=[i[0] for i in data],\n",
    "    notch=True,\n",
    ")\n",
    "plt.title('Household Income by Household Size')\n",
    "plt.xlim(-10_000,200_000)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Household Income')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Household Size');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Fancy Figures\n",
    "\n",
    "More complex visualizations can be created using Seaborn,\n",
    "and are not too hard to create by following and modifying\n",
    "recipes found on the [gallery](https://seaborn.pydata.org/examples/index.html) \n",
    "in the Seaborn documention.  As an example, this code snippet\n",
    "is lightly edited from the recipe offered for\n",
    "[overlapping ridge plots](https://seaborn.pydata.org/examples/kde_ridgeplot.html)."
   ]
  },
  {

   "source": [
    "sns.set(style=\"white\", rc={\"axes.facecolor\": (0, 0, 0, 0)})\n",
    "\n",
    "# Initialize the FacetGrid object\n",
    "pal = sns.cubehelix_palette(10, rot=-.25, light=.7)\n",
    "g = sns.FacetGrid(\n",
    "    hh[hh.income<=300_000], row=\"hhsize5\", hue=\"hhsize5\", \n",
    "    aspect=7, height=1.25, palette=pal,\n",
    "    xlim=(-95000,300000)\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Draw the densities in a few steps\n",
    "g.map(sns.kdeplot, \"income\", clip_on=False, fill=True, alpha=1, lw=1.5, bw_adjust=0.5)\n",
    "g.map(sns.kdeplot, \"income\", clip_on=False, color=\"w\", lw=4, bw_adjust=0.5)\n",
    "g.map(plt.axhline, y=0, lw=2, clip_on=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Define and use a simple function to label the plot in axes coordinates\n",
    "def label(x, color, label):\n",
    "    ax = plt.gca()\n",
    "    ax.text(0, .15, f'{label} Persons', fontweight=\"bold\", color=color,\n",
    "            ha=\"left\", va=\"center\", transform=ax.transAxes)\n",
    "\n",
    "g.map(label, \"income\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Set the subplots to overlap\n",
    "g.fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=-0.625)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Remove axes details that don't play well with overlap\n",
    "g.set_titles(\"\")\n",
    "g.set(yticks=[], ylabel=\"\",\n",
    "      xticks=[       0,50_000,100_000,150_000,200_000,300_000], \n",
    "      xticklabels=['0','50K' ,'100K' ,'150K' ,'200K'  ,'300K',],\n",
    "     )\n",
    "g.despine(bottom=True, left=True);\n",
    "g.row_names = [f'HH Size {i}' for i in g.row_names]"
   ]
  }
